[1
Date: Thu, 27 Apr 2000 15:09:19 -0400
From: Morken, Tim <tim9@cdc.gov>

I would be interested to know if the information in the article from the
(Penn) Valley Independent 22 Apr 2000 [edited concerning rabies is
accurate in it's description of a dog being put in quarantine for 3 months.
If the dog had a previous rabies vaccine, a booster and a 6-week home
quarantine is all that is necessary. There are no reports of a vaccinated
animal developing rabies or the ability to transmit rabies after contact
with a rabid animal.
Also, saliva or other body fluid contact of a rabid animal is not
transmissible through intact skin, so casual contact is not a real concern.
My comments are based on research and personal experience.
--
Tim Morken, BA, EMT(MSA), HTL(ASCP)
Infectious Disease Pathology Activity
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
Atlanta, GA 30333 USA
e-mail: tim9@cdc.gov
